         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... The king speaks: “What shall I do?” ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">What should I do?</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>230</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>35</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Or why do you prepare to give gifts ..., not paying attention to my command? ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Or why do you prepare to give gifts …, not paying attention to my command?</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>541</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>214</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... is, you refrain from giving gifts ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>12</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>728</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[is] the wish, even if I should starve to death already in this birth, a gift (?) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>144</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Such (speech) I do not offer to say.” 1. Excited into bitterness, the Purohita says </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">and for the sake of [your] own desire not caring for the misery of the country ....</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>214</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[since] he did not refrain ... (from such) speech [and] (did not care (?) about) the king’s anger...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they speak to the Brahmin: “ Fie, o Brahmin ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">as a bad person you are not able. The lord is finding pleasure in giving ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(whether) this town (Aru)ṇāvatī does not deride you. You [are] a mean person ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels"><ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht78"/></note><note type="philcomment">This text contains a conversation and argument between the king and Purohita [Brahmin], who does not share the king’s generosity towards supplicants. In <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht78"/> the argument between the king and the vidūṣaka [Brahmin] immediately follows the dialogue of the king and the queen, where the king emphasises the fact that he would even give his own life to a supplicant. Thus it makes sense that <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a343"/> should follow <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht78"/>.</note><note type="philcomment">In the story as related in this text and the continuing fragment <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht81"/>, there is a gap of unknown length, which may comprise perhaps less than a leaf’s length, but no more than two or three leaves: King Araṇemi drives the Brahmin Rudramukha out of the country before the eyes of his followers – which amounts to a serious insult. Rudramukha betakes himself to a different country where he opens a Brahmin school. All his thoughts and desire are bent on taking revenge on king Araṇemi.</note><note type="philcomment">The translation follows <bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt2001"/><citedRange>308-9</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>35</citedRange></bibl> and <bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">This fragment must be placed after <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a344"/> and, according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>35-6</citedRange></bibl>, before <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a342"/>. <bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt2001"/><citedRange>305, 308</citedRange></bibl> places A 342 first.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="lingcomment">Translation as above <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>541</citedRange></bibl>. <bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt2001"/><citedRange>309</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>35</citedRange></bibl> and <bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1954b"/><citedRange>261</citedRange></bibl> have more or less “Or why do you not regard my order [and] get excited [about] giving gifts at all?”. Instead of 'you get excited', Couvreur (op. cit.) suggests as alternative 'you continue'.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">This line seems to contain a verse of 4x18 syllables, rhythm 7/7/4.</note></p>
         </div>
